<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-680-223  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 680 223.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Reseller News  Dec 10 1990 n398 p3(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Calculating returns; vendors eye Windows accounting software.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Shore, Joel.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Several companies, including Microsoft Corp, are exploring thefeasibility of developing accounting software that runsexclusively on Windows 3.0, although customer demand is said to bescant.andP;  Microsoft feels that in-house development of an accountingpackage would take too long.andP;  Therefore, the company is searchingfor a partner to develop and license to Microsoft an entry-level,Windows-based business accounting system.andP;  DacEasy Inc., a makerof entry-level accounting packages, was approached by Microsoftbut no agreement was made.andP;  The company is currently up for sale.andO;Sources contend that SBT Corp. of Sausalito, CA, is planning tointroduce a Windows accounting package imminently.andP;  Someaccounting software vendors are currently developing Windowsproducts but others are holding back, due to the lack of customerdemand.andP;  Some feel, however, that the shift to Windows isinevitable.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Microsoft Corp. (Product development)Software Business Technology Corp. (Product development)DacEasy Inc. (Management).andO;Ticker:    MSFT.andO;Product:   Microsoft Windows 3.0 (Graphical user interface) (Usage).andO;Topic:     AccountingSoftware PackagesProduct DevelopmentMarket Analysis.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>